Provide @SafeVarargs for ListAssert and IterableAssert

  This will **breaks** several method return type: there was a lot of cast from ListAssert to SELF while SELF
  was technically a IterableAssert (which ListAssert isn't!) and in some other place, ListAssert was returned
  instead of (new) SoftAssertionListAssert.

  A new factory method had been added in AbstractIterableAssert to allow implementation to provide the "best"
  AbstactListAssert implementation (so that SoftAssertionIterableAssert returns SoftAssertionListAssert).

First commit of the buckabuckaboo repo

Changed the screen width and height calculation to occur at each valid mouse ping event; also simplified initialization by determining the src automatically, and provided an init function which wraps the variable and event definitions.

Shifted the automatic page definition (the 'src' value sent to the server) to occur at each valid mouse ping event, like screen height and width, since browsers cache the buckabuckaboo.min.js file and the value of src won't change if the plugin is being used on more than one page on the same domain.

Initial update

actions: move core actions to GtkBuilder XML

Gather all the scattered lists of document- and view-level actions
together in one place. Keeps the code tidy, and hopefully it's easier to
maintain.

Review action labels and tooltips for capitalization and uniqueness.
Also fix a few minor bugs here and there (visualize_rendering_cb(),
initialization of _show_subwindows).

app/doc/layer: minor cleanups and documentation

No significant code changes.

Improve button mapping, spring-loaded modes

New look for the button mapping preferences tab, allowing more actions
to be tied to pointer buttons and combinations of modifier keys. Added
support for more than 3 buttons, allowing Wacom pad buttons to be
assigned to MyPaint functions. Actions can now have more than one button
combination pointed at them.

Removed all the hardcoded button mappings. Everything is now managed in
user preferences. Space is now a fake Button2, and responds to the same
bindings.

Updated button mapping defaults: Ctrl equivalents for all Alt+button
combos. Popup menu is now on Button3 where it belongs - my personal
preference because I don't use colour history, but it can be set back to
the old color history behaviour in preferences.

Some interaction modes are now spring-loaded, which means that if
they're started with button-modifier combinations, they cancel when the
modifiers and button are released.

Mode classes now use cooperative supercalls, to allow common code to be
shared via mixins. More modes are now zoomable and rotatable with the
mouse wheel, but support's still lacking for mode-switching via the
button map and also modifier+drag translations, rotations and zooms in
some of the fancier modes.

app: function access to the singleton

Add support for "from gui.application import get_app" so that widgets
constructed from glade can get required handles onto the application
singleton without requiring a ref to it as a constructor argument, or
dubious calls to set_app() methods during their lifetime. Simplifies
writing glade-compatible widgets, at the expense of something that smells a
lot like a global variable.

Tidy imports while we're at it.

workspace: integrate tab-based layout replacement

Begin using the new gui.workspace layout code. This replaces a large chunk
of old, crufty code with a nicer system that makes better use of the screen
space and is built more closely on top of internal Gtk types.

User improvements/changes:
 * Sidebars are now present on both sides of the screen.
 * Drag tabs around to reorder and to move docked tools between
   sidebars and a floating window state.
 * Fullscreen is a bit more understandable: there's an auto-hide timeout,
   and poking the sides of the screen or hovering over a hidden floating
   window reveals the hidden controls.
 * Fullscreen state is remembered between invocations now.

Various debug prints: replace w/ standard logging

Python has a standard logging module with lots of goodies. Categorization
of messages and module reporting to name just two. Let's start using it in
place of print (or print(), considering Python 3).

brushsettingswin: remove, replaced by new editor

Remove the old brush settings window fully, now there's a feature-complete
replacement.

options_widget: add for various modes

Add an options panel for drawing modes, view manipulation modes, and the
frame editing mode.

This is a little gem. Perhaps the Knuth routine is better when it's
correct, but this little version (even though it generates all
partitions and the desired one must be selected) is pretty nice.

The table below shows the number of unique partitions obtained
by paritioning n items into 4 groups; the time is also indicated.

n P  time(s)
5 10 0.0
6 65 0.0
7 350 0.01
8 1701 0.03
9 7770 0.11
10 34105 0.62
11 145750 3.82

When multiset_partitions is given a list that contains only

and then the enumerated multiset is returned.

Single Python 2 and 3 compatible codebase

Refactor the codebase to be both Python 2 and 3 compatable. Main changes
include:

- Absolute imports with leading `.`.

- Python 3 print function rather than print statement.

- String in Python 3 are always unicode, so unicode related functions
  have been removed.

- Integers in Python 3 are always "long", `long` methods and suffixing
  long numbers with `L` are not supported

- `map`, `filter`, and `range` return iterables rather than lists, where
  needed, wrap these calls in `list()`. As such, the Python 2 iterable
  forms of these, such as `xrange` and `ifilter`, have been removed.

- `exec` is a function rather than a statement.

- Iterators in Python 3 do not have `.next()` methods. Instead, `next()`
  can be used (Python >=2.6).

Changes related to Python 2 and 3 compatibility are in
sympy.core.compatibility.

WARNING: A lot of changes to the existing API and the event system.

This WILL break existing API clients and probably some event handlers too. I'm sorry for the disruptive changes, but I needed to rectify some decisions before they went too far utilized elsewhere to still be corrected.

 Basically this change completely removes the old API and switches it (same endpoint) with the new one, that's basically the existing AJAX API that the client uses, but way more RESTful and based on JSON (exception being the file upload).

 The event system has been revamped to carry more payload data (and in an extensible form as dictionary, to allow for later addition of attributes to single events), with the existing event listeners adjusted to also allow users to make use of this data in their consumers.

 Documentation has been greatly enhanced for the REST API (and is still being added to), the events will be documented here as well.

Lots of changes:

- GCODE viewer now supports multiple extruders and configurable bed sizes
- GCODE viewer also now based on callbacks and config injection instead of dependence on elements in the embedding website
- Switched GCODE viewer to bootstrap-slider for the layer/command sliders, patched bootstrap-slider a bit up (TODO: PR to upstream)
- GCODE interpreter in backend also calculates filament usage for all extruders
- More consequent use of LESS, switched bootstrap to LESS source to have access to variables and mixins, introduced config setting to switch between usage of compiled CSS (checked in as well) or LESS, defaults to CSS

First version of OctoPrint with i18n/l10n support

Also included is a translation for (informal) german.

New languages can be added with "python setup.py babel_new --locale=<language code>" which will create the corresponding .po file from the existing .pot file under "src/octoprint/translations/<language code>". Translations can be refreshed from strings in source with "python setup.py babel_refresh". Existing translations can be compiled into usable translation files (.mo for python and .js for Javascript) via "python setup.py babel_compile".

 You'll need to install the development dependencies for all of this to work, just issue "pip install -r requirements-dev.txt"

 Note: numbers are not yet correctly formatted for their respective locale (e.g. "2.5mm" instead of "2,5mm" in german).

Try to reconnect to backend when switching from ap to wifi

netconnectd now regularly pings hostname it got from backend (defaults to <systemname>.local) while switching to wifi from ap mode and reloads page to that if host comes up.

This requires the browser the client is currently running in to be able to resolve local domains as broadcasted via avahi. Windows systems will need to install the Bonjour for Windows client for this to work.

View models can now implement getAdditionalControls to add controls to the control tab

Controls may now contain a new property "javascript" which may be either a javascript function to be called when the control is executed, or a string to be eval'd when the control is executed. If it is a function, it will be called with the config of the custom control as single parameter "data". If it is a string it will be eval'd within a function context providing the custom control configuration as variable data.

Additionally controls may contain a new property "enabled", which may also be either a javascript function or a string to be eval'd. The custom control config will be available to the enabled code as described above. The code is expected to return true if the component should be enabled or false if not.

Speedup to_dict with sqlalchemy.inspection

I've spent some time on figuring out what could be done to improve the performance of
flask-restless. Since most of the time consumption seems to come from to_dict I started from there.

It shortly showed up that the way the columns of the current result are being retrieved is not optimal.
The hybrid_method stuff is rather expensive, even if no or just a few hybrid properties
exist.

Since sqlalchemy 0.8 there is an inspect() method (sqlalchemy.inspection.inspect) which does what
has previosuly been done using mro & isinstance and the object_mapper calls.

I've create a rather simple test case:

	class Parent(db.Model):
		id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
		name = db.Column(db.String(10), unique=True)
		childs = db.relationship('Child')

		@hybrid_property
		def test(self):
		    return '%s-test' % self.name
	class Child(db.Model):
		id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
		name = db.Column(db.String(10), unique=True)
		parent_id = db.Column(db.ForeignKey('parent.id'))
		parent = db.relationship('Parent')

Create a Parent, add 100 Child's and pass the parent (with deep for childs) to to_dict.

Here is a line-profiler result of the unoptimized version (upstream/master @
1d81d6486fef4fe8c5b0051ec772e2f53dc16eb3):

	Function: to_dict at line 228
	Total time: 23.377 s

	Line #      Hits         Time  Per Hit   % Time  Line Contents
	==============================================================
	   [..]
	   270     50500       134320      2.7      0.6      if (exclude is not None or exclude_relations is not None) and \
	   271                                                       (include is not None or include_relations is not None):
	   272                                                   raise ValueError('Cannot specify both include and exclude.')
	   273                                               # create a list of names of columns, including hybrid properties
	   274     50500       118004      2.3      0.5      try:
	   275    252000      1259072      5.0      5.4          columns = [p.key for p in object_mapper(instance).iterate_properties
	   276    201500       613966      3.0      2.6                     if isinstance(p, ColumnProperty)]
	   277                                               except UnmappedInstanceError:
	   278                                                   return instance
	   # first hotspot here:
	   279    252500       702816      2.8      3.0      for parent in type(instance).mro():
	   280   2121000      5514722      2.6     23.6          columns += [key for key, value in parent.__dict__.items()
	   281   1919000      5627984      2.9     24.1                      if isinstance(value, hybrid_property)]
	   [..]
	   298    202000       602245      3.0      2.6      for key, value in result.items():
	   299                                                   # TODO We can get rid of this when issue #33 is resolved.
	   300    151500       520331      3.4      2.2          if isinstance(value, datetime.date):
	   301                                                       result[key] = value.isoformat()
	   302    151500       476480      3.1      2.0          elif isinstance(value, uuid.UUID):
	   303                                                       result[key] = str(value)
	   #  next hotspot here:
	   304    151500      5372080     35.5     23.0          elif is_mapped_class(type(value)):
	   305                                                       result[key] = to_dict(value)
	   [..]

Both of the previously recognized 'hotspots' are no longer that heavy. Due to inspection we can also
re-use some of the information gathered for the column list in order to avoid expensive type-checks.

Even thought all tests are still passing I'm not 100% certain this optimized code works in all
circumstances.

Tests had been performed by using the following script:

	from flask import Flask
	from flask.ext.sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
	from flask.ext.restless.helpers import to_dict
	from sqlalchemy.ext.hybrid import hybrid_property
	import line_profiler

	profile = line_profiler.LineProfiler()
	profile.add_function(to_dict)

	app = Flask(__name__)
	app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite://'
	db = SQLAlchemy(app)

	class Parent(db.Model):
	  id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
	  name = db.Column(db.String(10), unique=True)
	  childs = db.relationship('Child')

	  @hybrid_property
	  def test(self):
	    return '%s-test' % self.name

	class Child(db.Model):
	  id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
	  name = db.Column(db.String(10), unique=True)
	  parent_id = db.Column(db.ForeignKey('parent.id'))
	  parent = db.relationship('Parent')

	db.create_all()

	parent = Parent(name='parent-%d' % 1)
	db.session.add(parent)
	db.session.commit()

	for ci in range(0,100):
	  child = Child(parent_id=parent.id, name='child-%d-%d' % (1, ci))
	  db.session.add(child)

	db.session.commit()

	if __name__ == "__main__":

	  from timeit import Timer

	  profile.enable()
	  def test():
	    to_dict(parent, deep={'childs': []})

	  timer = Timer(stmt=test)
	  print timer.repeat(5, number=100)
	  profile.disable()
	  profile.print_stats()
	  profile.dump_stats('to_dict.lprof')
